{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_parsifal_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608658/1957112801/1057.xml":{"full_text":"WEATHER FORECAST\nCloudy and mild with occasional rain, low\nnear 52 tonight. Cloudy and mild with rain\nlikely Friday. (Full report on Page A-2.)\nTemperatures Today\nMidnight 50 6 am-. 48 10 am. .J. 54\n3am 48 8 a.m.-..4811 \u00bb.m. \u2014B7\n4 aja. 49 9 a.m. 50Noon 58\n106th Year. No. 332. Phone ST. 3-5000\nEisenhowers At Church Servic\nlit\n*mm in. *S9Bk 9 i 4 9\nfjSk\nW9|W|i\na B j\u00dff\nP* ST x 'F m mk\nftffffr- I\u2019frrfiYfi^T'^ 1 jpg\u2019 i|^^H|^^H^^H\u00dffl^^^^^R|^Hfl^^H\u00dffl^H\u00dfH|\nS i 9\n'A, Si 111\nJr M?\nS S h| JBm\n19 C9L jpjp j\nSf jp ji s\nsOak .3b 3\u00a3jre& JH\n9 p jj n\nf HBi f m\nIf 4? *M\nJm '3k. w\u00dfMffli j- f\nW W-flt\n|BK fi J\n\nI4# v\nr|J||\nBrangj& mm \u00ab9r Jf m\nwmfm W 9 I b\nft- jL JHHj\nHE. tos JB\n\nBl\u2019r-ffffingfc. f-B m *1 \u00abB\nHp BHe i, 3y\nittif m\nfe\nm\n9\n3; I\ni y |m a s y #N \u2019^i^\u2019v\nA >\\-.v,\u2019 s M\nf r 'iMMm\nSURPRISE VISIT TO CHURCH SERVICE\u2014\nPresident Eisenhower holds the hand of his\nwife as they reach the National Presbyterian\nNixon at White House, Extends Ro!e\nIn Making Key Decisions for U. S.\nBy JOHN V. HORNER\nVice President Nixon, stead\nily extending his participation\nin administration affairs,\ndropped in at the White House\non this Thanksgiving holiday\nto see, he said, \"if I can be\nof any help\u201d in the situation\ncreated by President Eisenhow\ner's illness.\nThe Nation's No. 2 office\nholder, who predicted after\nseeing President Eisenhower\nyesterday that the Chief\nExecutive will recover com\npletely and \"sooner than would\nnormally be the case,\u201d arrived\nat 0:15 am. and headed for\nthe office of Sherman Adams.\nHe said he was \"just stop\nping by to see If there are\nPHONE SERVICE\nFOR TODAY\nTha Star's holiday telephone iem\nka\u00ab will observe the following dos\ning hoars today:\nClassified Deportment, 9 pm.\n(Classified ads may be placed in\nperson at the business counter in\nThe Star lobby to 9 p.m.i\nCirculation Deportment, 9:30 p.m.\nMain Switchboard, 12 midnight.\nNight service lines will be placed\nin operation following closing of\ni main switchboard.\nany loose ends I could take\ncare of.\"\nIn addition to his optimistic\nprediction of Mr. Eisenhower's\nrecovery, the Vice President\nstated categorically that there\nis no thought or even discus\nsion in official circles of the\nPresident\u2019s resigning from office\nbecause of his latest Incapacity.\nNixon Helped Decide\nAt an unprecedented news\nconference in the White House\nlast night, Mr. Nixon made the\nsurprising revelation that Pres\nident Eisenhower Aid not par\nticipate in the final decision to\nauthorize the production of\nboth the Air Force Thor and\nand the Army Jupiter Inter\nmediate-range ballistic missiles.\nThe final decision, he dis\nclosed, was made by himself\nand seven other high-ranking\nofficials, all of whom are ap\npointees of the administration.\nMr. Nixon said, however, that\nPresident Elsenhower had ap\nproved the basic plan for the\nproduction of both missiles\nwhen it was outlined* to him\nlast week by Secretary of De\nfense McElroy. It was on Mon\nday that the President was\nstricken with a temporary stop\npage of blood in a small branch\ntttery of the brain. He has\n\u00aek Iheniirg Slaf\nV V WnH SUNDAY MORNING EDITION /**W L/\nWASHINGTON, D. C., THURSDAY, NOVEMBER 28, 1957-96 PAGES\nChurch this morning to. attend services less\nthan four days after the President was stricken\nill.\u2014Star Staff Photo by A. C. Chinn.\nparticipated in no major policy\ndecision since then.\nThe Vice President, besieged\nby questions during a 45-min\nute session In the office of Pres\nidential Press Secretary James\nC. Hagerty, said the Anal deci\nslon was made Ipy the eight\nmember group at a White\nHouse meeting Tuesday after\nnoon. The authorization was\nannounced yesterday by Secre\ntary McElroy in a statement\nprepared for the Senate Armed\nServices Preparedness Subcom\nmittee.\nQueried on Details\nPerspiring slightly in an office\npacked tight by standing re\nporters, bustling cameramen\nand the glaring light equipment\nof newsreel photographers, the\nVice President said these were\nthe men who acted with him in\nreaching the Important decision\non the missiles:\nSecretary McElroy, Secretary\nof State Dulles, Undersecretary\nof Defense Quarles, Dr. James\nKillian, new special assistant\nto the Presideni for science and\ntechnology: William M. Hola\nday, director of the Defense\nDepartment's guided missile\nprogram: Budget Director Per\ncival Brundage and Mr.\nCoMtinued on Page A-4, CoL 1\nPrayersOfffered\nFor Eisenhower\nPeace rested like a benedic\ntion on Americans here and\ni abroad today as a grateful Na\ntion celebrated Thanksgiving.\nIn Washington as elsewhere,\nprayers were mingled with tra-\nPicture of Pan American Man,\nl| Page A-1\u00bb\nditlonal feasting and merrl\n-1 ment. Singly and in family\ngroups, people expressed their\ngratitude for past blessings.\nMillions offered prayers for\nPresident Eisenhower who is\nrecovering from a slight stroke.\nPresident and Mrs. Elsenhow\ni er paid a surprise visit them\nselves to National Presbyterian\ni Church less than four days\nafter the Chief Executive was\nstricken.\ni The weather was warm and\npartly cloudy. Mild tempera\ntures and occasional rain this\nafternoon and tonighf were\nforecast.\nMenus Feature Turkey\nTurkey was the main item on\nThanksgiving menus every\n-1 where. It was the feature of\nmost meals in area homes as\ni well as in prisons, hospitals and\n1 other institutions.\nAs families gathered to count\ntheir blessings, television also\nl\u2018 See HOUDAT, Page A-1\nTrip to Paris\nNext Month\nHeld Possible\nRecovering Rapidly,\nPresident Talks\nOs Trip to Farm 4\nBULLETIN\nPresident and Mrs. Eisen\nhower \u201chope\u201d to go to their\nGettysburg (Pa.) farm to\nmorrow, White House Press\nSecretary James C. Hagerty\nsaid today. He said it has\nnot been determined how\nlong they will remain there.\nBy GARNETT D. HORNER\nPresident Eisenhower made\na surprise trip to Thanksgiving\nchurch services today and left\nopen the possibility that he still\nmay go to the NATO summit\nmeeting in Paris next month.\nGiving dramatic evidence of\nwhat an aide called almost un\nbelievable rapid recovery prog\nress from what most people\nwould can a stroke, the Presi\ndent escorted Mrs. Eisenhower\nto the National Presbyterian\nChurch at 11 am.\nDolling his hat and smiling\nbroadly, the Presid\u00dft said\n\u201cthank you very much\u201d to a\nnews photographer who wished\nhim a \u201chappy Thanksgiving\u201d\nas he walked into the church.\nThe President, wearing a blue\ntopcoat and gray hat, was\nfrowning a bit as he stepped\nout of his limousine at the\nchurch entrance.\nNo Sign of Illness\nBut he showed no evidence of\nillness as he put his hand on\nMrs. Eisenhower\u2019s arm and es\ncorted her across the sidewalk.\nMr. Eisenhower left the\nWhite House for the church\nservice as White House Press\nSecretary\u2018James C. Hagerty was\ntelling newsmen that he was\n\u201cnojh conscious of anything\nwrong\u201d with the President\u2019s\nspeech during a 20-minute talk\nwith him this morning.\nA slight difficulty in saying'\nlong words had been the only\nsymptom noted by the Presi\ndent\u2019s doctors of the, blockage\nof a small branch artery in his\nbrain which he suffered Mon\nday afternoon.\n\u201cV could not believe there\ncould be such improvement as\nthere has been\u201d in the Presi\ndent\u2019s speech between yester\nday morning and this morning,\nMr. Hagerty said.\nStatement ea Meeting\nIn regard to the NATO\nCouncil meeting, Mr. Hagerty\nread a statement approved by\nthe President\u2014which was in\nItself a surprise. The state\nment follows:\n\u201cThe President had looked\nforward to attending the NATO\nheads of government meeting.\nHis doctors will decide later\nwhether he can make the trip.\nIf the President finds he cannot\ngo, he will ask the Vice Presi\ndent to head the United States\ndelegation.\u201d\nOnly Tuesday evening, the\nWhite House and State De\npartment had informed the\nNATO allies that it was go be\n\u201cassumed\u201d that the President\nwould not be able to attend\nthe mid-December meeting.\nThis was in view of an esti\nmate then by his doctors that\nhe would require several weeks\nof rat and decreased activities\nAsked if today\u2019s announce\nment leaving open the possi\nbility that Mr. Eisenhower still;\nmight make the Paris trip re-!\nfleeted a more optimistic view\nabout how quickly he may re- 1\ncover completely, Mr. Hagerty\nreplied with a flat \u201cyes.\u201d\nMr. Hagerty said neither he!\nnor anyone else on the White\nContinued on Page A-7, Col. 1 j\nPresident Told Questioners in April\nStroke Would Not Cause Him to Quit\nBy JAY HAYDEN\nTaking President Eisenhower\nat his own word, uttered last\nApril 3, it will require some\nthing much more serious than,\nhis present mild \u201cstroke\u201d to l\nInduce him to resign his Job to\nVice President Nixon.\nSpeaking at a press confer\nence on that date the President\nsaid:\n\"There could be a case where\na man would have a stroke\nthat was slight, from which he\ncoujjd recover. We Yiave great\nstatesmen in the world today'\nthat have recovered from a\ncouple of them and carried on\nfor years.\"\nThat statement is the more\nremarkable because it came in\nresponse to an assault from two\ndirections.\nFirst, the President was\nasked for comment on the as\nsertion by two leading news\npapers that he was all set to\nU. S. to Speed Output\nOs Jupiter and Thor\nSr Um Assoc Ik t*d Mo\nThe United States, striving\nto catch up with Russia in\nmedium range missiles, has\nordered two rival types into\nproduction. The goal is to\nhave them ready for use in\nanother year.\nThe Senate Preparedness\nSubcommittee, to which Secre\ntary of Defense McElroy made\nthe announcement at a hearing\nyesterday, welcomed it as \u201cgood\nnews\u201d and termed Mr. McElroy\na man \u201cwith both the power\nand the willingness to act.\u201d\nChairman Lyndon B. John\nson, Democrat of Texas, said\nSecretary McElroy is the \u201creal\nczar\u201d in the battle to surpass\nRussia in missile development,\nand told reporters he hoped\nthat other decisions which Mr.\nMcElroy promised \u201cwill come\njust as soon as possible.\u2019\nQuarles Testifies\nThe subcommittee, before\nrecessing its hearings until De\ncember 13, also heard Deputy\nSecretary Donald A. Quarles\ntestify that this country is run\nning \u201cneck-and-neck\u201d with\nRussia in developing the Inter\ncontinental ballistic missile\n(ICBM) and that \u201cas a whole,\nas of today,\u201d the over-all\nContinued on Page A-9, Cot 1\nMohamed's Son Orders\nTroops to Resist Spain\ni RABAT, Morocco, Nov. 28 (A\u201d).\n\u2014Crown Prince Moulay Hassan\ni charged today that Spanish\nforces had launched attacks\nagainst Moroccan territory from\nthe colony of Ifni and an\nnounced he had given orders\nto the royal army to fight back.\nAn earUer report by the Mo\nroccan nationalist newspaper\nMohamad V Leaves Woikinstoo lor\nVirginia Visit. Pspo A-6\nA1 Alam said Spaniards in Ifni\nhad started an aM-QUt attack\nagainst rebels in Ifn* early to\nday. and were bombing Moroc\ncan villages. The paper said\nMoroccan antiaircraft guns al\nready had fired on some of the\nplanes.\nThe Prince, in a radio\nstatement broadcast in Arabic,\nsaid two Moroccan women had\nbeen killed in Moroccan terri\ntory by shells fired by Spanish\ntroops.\nMoulay Hassan said that\n\u201cfollowing Spanish Incursions\non Moroccan territory\u201d he had\ngiven orders to the royal army\nto fire at any foreign plane\nover Morocco whose mission\nwas believed to be hostile.\nBeady to Defend Territory\nThe Moroccan Army, he add\ned, \u201cla ready to defend Its ter\nritory against anyone.\u201d\nThe prince has sent one of\nhis top aides. Col. Moulay Hafld,\nto the United States to confer\nwith King Mohamed V who is\non a visit there. Reports from\nWashington said the colonel\nwas expected to see the King\nin Dallas tomorrow. The Crown\nPrince la heading the Moroccan\ngovernment while his father is\naway.\nMoulay Hassan said Morocco\nhad been surprised by the re\nbellion which broke out in the\nIfni colony on the Atlantic\ncoast last Saturday.\nHe declared Morocco hoped\nto settle the affair through ne\ngotiations because Generalis\nsimo Francisco Franco had\nshown \u201cgreat comprehension.\u201d\nj But he said South Morocco,\nstill under a Spanish protec\ntorate. was of great \u201ceconomic\nand strategic importance\u201d be\ncause \"it is our door opened\non the Sahara.\u201d South Mor\nocco is south of Ifni.\nRebel Positions Sought\nA1 Alam said the Spanish\n\u2019attack was designed to recover\nI positions lost to the rebels.\nhand over his job to Mr. Nixon\nlif and when affairs quieted\ndown. To that one Mr. Eisen\nhower replied that \u201cit is the\nworst rot I have heard since\njl have been in office.\u201d\nSecondly, he was criticized\nfor his recommendation that\ndecision as to when a President\nis Incapacitated should be left\nup to a majority vote of the\ncabinet. Said Mr. Eisenhower:\n\"Now the Vice President, as\nwe see under the wording of\nthe Constitution, has to decide.\nBut he has always been re\nluctant to do It because he\nsays, \u2018How would we turn It\nback at the end?\u2019 or \u2018Do I be\ncome President for the whole\ntime or am I acting Prevident\nor a real President?\u2019 And it is\nastonishing how full the rec\nords are of contrary opinions\non this.\u201d\nSo, said Mr. Eisenhower, \u201cWe\nsaid, all right, the cabinet is\nHome Delivered: gjg leSo CENTS\nI^J^jjjj^P\nALLEN DULLES\nLeaving Missile Hearing\n\u2014AT Phot*\nThe newspaper said the at\ntack began about 1 a.m. It re\nported another \u201cdeadly battle\u201d\ntook place yesterday at Souk\nElkhemls, about 15 miles east\nof the colonial capital of Sidi\nIfni, and that rebels captured\nthree truckloads of arms.\nA1 Alam, the organ of the\nIstiqlal (independence) Party,\ncharged Spanteh planes bombed\nseveral Moroccan villages south\nof the colony. Moroccan anti\naircraft batteries opened fire\non the planet, the paper aaid.\nNationalists said the Spanish\nliner Virgen de Africa landed\n1.800 Spanish tjoop reinforce\nments at Ifni yesterday and\nthat another tranport was ex\npected today.\nMadrid dispatches last night\nsaid two troopships left Al\ngeciras with four infantry regi\nments and that 150 paratroop\ners were flown from Madrid\nto reinforce the colony.\nA rebel communique yester\nday said 115 Spaniards' were\nkilled or wounded In fighting\nstarting last Saturday. The\nSpaniards, acknowledging five\nof their own soldiers killed,\nclaimed 100 casualties were in\nflicted on the rebels.\nSpain has rejected formal\nMoroccan requests for the 741-\nsquare-mile colony on the At\nlantic coast to be turned over\nto the Rabat government.\nThe colony Is surrounded on\nthree sides by Morocco but\nSpain claims the Moroccan\ngovernment has never been able\nto establish its authority in the\nsurrounding area.\nGlobemaster Crashes\nAt Ankara, 3 Killed\nANKARA, Turkey, Nov. 28\nUP). \u2014A United States globe\nmaster transport plane today\ncrashed into a hill near Ankara\nkilling three of the eight\npassengers.\nFirst reports said the globe\nmaster crashed in thick fog.\nTwo passengers were reported\nseriously Injured. No further\ndetails were immediately avail\nable.\nReds Fire on Quemoy\nTAIPEI. Nov. 28 UP- \u2014The\nChinese Communists fired 98\nshells at the offshore islands\nof Quemoy and Little Quemoy\nlate yesterday and early today,\nthe Defense Ministry reported.\nappointed by the President.\nSo, if the Vice President de\ncides the President is out of\ncirculation for a brief time or\nlonger time, he goes to the\ncabinet. lays it before them\nand if a majority of the cabi\nnet, presumably friends of the\nPresident, appointed by him,\nsay: 'Yes. that\u2019s right.\u2019 he (the\nVice President) takes over. And\nuntil the President is again\nable to say \u2018I now resume. I am\nable to resume office,\u2019 he would\ncontinue to act in that ca\npacity.\u201d\nThis painstaking discussion\nby Mr. Eisenhower of the prob\nlems raised by his uncertain\nhealth was by no means unique.\nFor example, much is being\nmade of his assertion, March\n7, 1955. Incident to announce\nment of his candidacy for re\nelection. that If his health ever\nfails to a point where he could\nBce DISABILITY, l>age A-4\nHoliday\nEdition\nNo Night Final Editions Today\nNATO Council\nWilling to Talk\nWith Nixon\nParis Parley Plans\nGo Ahead Despite\nEisenhower Illness\nPARIS, Nov. 28 (A*).\u2014Paul-\nHenrl Spaak, secretary general\nof the North Atlantic Treaty\nOrganisation, today announced\nthat the summit meeting of,\nNATO\u2019s chiefs of government'\nwould go ahead as planned de\nspite the illness of President\nEisenhower.\nA communique issued after\na meeting of the permanent\nNATO Council said the group\nhad \u201clearned with satisfaction\u201d\nthat Vice President Nixon will\nhead the American delegation\nfor the meeting.\nA member of the United\nStates delegation to NATO said\nyesterday Mr. Nixon had been\nproposed to the members ss a\nSubstitute for Mr. Elsenhower.\nBut Mr. Nixon said later In\nWashington that the statement\n\u201cwas not made at any direction\nfrom the White House.\u201d\nHope for Quick Recovery\nThe communique issued by\nMr. Spaak said:\n\u201cThe North Atlantic Council,\nhaving learned k with regret\nthat President Eisenhower will\nbe prevented from attending\nthe NATO Council meeting in\nDecember, decided that the\nmeeting should take place at\nthe level originally planned.\n\u201cIt learned with satisfaction\nthat Vice President Nixon\nwould lead the American dele\ngation.\n\u201cThe council expressed its\nhope for the quick recovery of\nPresident Eisenhower.\"\nThe possibility that Mr. Ei\nsenhower would be able to at\ntend the December 16-18 talks\nwas not ruled out in Washing\nton. James C. Hagerty, Whit#\nHouse press secretary, ana\nState Department Press Officer\nLincoln White both said Mr.\nEisenhower himself will decide\non United State* representa\ntion.\nThe meeting of Presidents\nand Premiers has been planned\naround Mr. Eisenhower\u2019s lead\nership to rally the Atlantia\nalliance against Soviet threats.\nWhen the State Department\nsaid it \"assumed\u201d he would be\nunable to attend, NATO mem\nbers were asked to reconsider\nplans for the meeting.\nUnanimous Decision\nIt was learned after the\ncouncil meeting that some dele\ngates .expressed reservations\nabout holding the summit talks\nas planned. They apparently\nfeared that they might not\nobtain their original objectives\nwithout the presence of Mr.\nEisenhower.\nThe final decision was unani\nmous, however. The subject\ntook only about 10 minutes of\na normal weekly council meet\ning which Included several\nhours discussion of routine ad\nministrative matters.\nThe delegates expressed hope\nfor the speedy recovery of the\nPresident.\nThe December meeting is,\nnormally attended by foan\u00a3n\naad finance ministers.---Some\ndiplomats had suggcgjjed that\nthe coming meeting; should be\nat this level with a summit\nconference postponed until\nspring, when Mr. Elsenhower\nmight be able to attend.\nU. 8. Makes Suggestion\nBut four of the largest NATO\nmembers indicated yesterday\nthey favored going ahead with\nthe summit meeting, accepting\na suggestion made here by the\nUnited States delegation that\nICr. Nixon might replace the\nPresident, i\nThe four, Britain. France,\nWest Oermany and Italy, wer*\nreported joined by the Nether\nlands, Iceland and some other\nNATO countries in early sup\nport for leaving plans un\nchanged. Only Oreece was first\nreported hesitant.\nTHE STAR SELECTS\nTOP PREP PLAYERS\nGRIDIRON HEROES seUcitJ (or\nTko Stor'i All-Prop team oro iotro\n4ucod oo lap A-36.\nKENYA rortlon land ot the\ncroooroads, kai tkroo oksmetnot\u2014\ntko Gkooo woy, tko Swrtk Africa\nway and tko aiodoroto way. Smitk\nHampstonc, jr., him up kit im\nprrtuoM of tkt calaay't to oh polit\nical makeup on Papa C-15.\nGuide for Readers\nAmaM'ti 1-26-271 Lett, Found ..A J\nClauitiod C-9-14 Motic C-2\nComics C-lt-19 Okituary |-24\nCrossword C-ll Sports A 36-19\nEditorial A-26 TV-Radio C-16-17\nEdit'l Articles A-27 Woman's\nFeature Papa C-IS Section 8-1-1]\nHave The Star Delivered to\nYour Home Daily and Sunday\nDial Sterling 3 5000","height":"28796","width":"18058"}}
